Sherwood Valley Band Of Pomo Indians
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: This site is located where Dead Cow Creek exits the Old Sherwood Reservation under the bridge where Sherwood Rd crosses the creek. Willow, bay, blackberry, water mint, fir, and ferns, are the primary riparian vegetation. The stream bed consisted of small rocks, gravel and silt. The surrounding land use patterns consist of housing and horse pasture on the west side and undeveloped land on the east side. There are no hydrological modifications besides the bridge which is high and wide enough to not usually interact with water flows.

OrganizationFormalName: Sherwood Valley Band Of Pomo Indians
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: This site is located on Dead Cow Creek just before a driveway crosses the creek. Willow, oak, blackberry, water mint, and unidentified aquatic plants are the primary riparian vegetation. The testing site is a wide pool. The stream bed consists of large, medium, and small rocks with sand and silt. The surrounding land use patterns consist of housing and gardens. There is a hydrological modification of a rocky stream crossing that kicks up silt into the water each time it is crossed.

OrganizationFormalName: Sherwood Valley Band Of Pomo Indians
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: This site is located on Dead Cow Creek just after the creek enters Tribal land on the northeast side of the property. Small oaks, manzanita, soap root, poison oak, ferns, moss, and grass are the primary riparian vegetation. The stream bed consists of large, small and medium rocks, some covered in moss. The surrounding land use patterns consist of undeveloped land where elk, deer, and wild boar roam, and a neighbor just on the other side of the fence has cattle. There are no hydrological modifications. This is generally one of the most pristine sites with no algae, trash, or other contamination observed.

OrganizationFormalName: Sherwood Valley Band Of Pomo Indians
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: This site is located on an unnamed tributary of Davis Creek where it exits Tribal land. Oak, manzanita, buckeye, and grass are the primary riparian vegetation. The stream bed consists of medium and small rocks, gravel, sand, and silt. The surrounding land use patterns consist of housing and undeveloped land with a dirt road just above the creek. There is some ongoing erosion happening at this location as the stream winds through a meadow, with vertical banks of bare earth starting to form.  There are no hydrological modifications.

OrganizationFormalName: Sherwood Valley Band Of Pomo Indians
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: This site is located on an unnamed tributary of Davis Creek near where it enters Tribal property just after three creeks merge with one another. Willow, bay, oak, blackberry, manzanita, poison oak, ferns and moss are the primary riparian vegetation. The  stream bed consisted of large, medium, and small rocks, and gravel. The surrounding land use patterns consist of housing and gardens. There is the hydrological modification of a large culvert under a dirt road just before the sampling site.

OrganizationFormalName: Sherwood Valley Band Of Pomo Indians
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: This site is a pond located north of Mitomkai Rd and east of Eastside Rd. Willow, blackberry, cattails, coyote brush, and pine are the primary riparian vegetation. The pond bottom consists of silt and clay. The surrounding land use patterns consist of housing, gardens, and apparently some kind of car salvage endeavor as the pond is surrounded in non-operable vehicles in various stages of disarray, often these vehicles are stuffed with trash. The pond itself is a hydrological modification of a human made dam.

OrganizationFormalName: Sherwood Valley Band Of Pomo Indians
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: This site is located on an unnamed tributary of Baechtel Creek near a culvert where it goes under Sherwood Hill Drive. Bay, madrone, fir, and blackberry are the primary riparian vegetation. The stream bed consists of large, medium, and small rocks, gravel, silt, and sand. The surrounding land use patterns consist of housing and a Tribal office. There is also cattle ranching on a neighboring property and the cattle have been known to cross over onto Tribal land.

OrganizationFormalName: Sherwood Valley Band Of Pomo Indians
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: This site is located on an unnamed tributary of Baechtel Creek where it enters Tribal land. Bay, madrone, fir, and blackberry are the primary riparian vegetation beneath a slope populated in conifers. The the stream bed consists of small rocks, gravel, sand, and silt. The surrounding land use patterns consist of undeveloped forest with cattle ranching on the neighboring parcel. There was a break in the fence as it crossed the stream. This could be a potential access point for the trespassing cattle although the stream itself does not provide a convenient crossing with a large fallen log across it, suspended above the water level. There are no hydrological modifications.

OrganizationFormalName: Sherwood Valley Band Of Pomo Indians
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: This site is located on Kawi Creek where it enters Tribal land. Bay, fir, poison oak, ferns, moss, grass, yellow dock, and blackberry are the primary riparian vegetation. Most of the fir trees were standing dead and beginning to fall over. The stream flow  cascades down from a ledge created by the borderline fence holding back debris with erosion below that has since been covered by moss. The stream bed consists of small rocks, gravel, and sand. The surrounding land use patterns consist of horse and cattle grazing on the neighboring parcel on the other side of the fence. There are no intentional hydrological modifications, although the fence separating the property has impacted the terrain of the creek bed.

OrganizationFormalName: Sherwood Valley Band Of Pomo Indians
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: This site is a pond located on the hill west of the Tribal Office. Bay, oak, madrone, manzanita, poison oak, coyote brush, blackberry, fir, and water mint are the primary riparian vegetation. The pond bottom is primarily silt and clay. The surrounding land use patterns consist of housing and gardens. There is also cattle ranching on a neighboring property, the cows have been known to cross the fence on to Tribal land. The pond itself is a hydrological modification as it is a human made dam.

OrganizationFormalName: Sherwood Valley Band Of Pomo Indians
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: This site is a pond located on the Sherwood Valley Rancheria Westside property on Cropley Lane. Willow, blackberry and cattails are the primary riparian vegetation. The pond is often a strange cloudy blue color. The pond bottom consists of silt and clay. The surrounding land use patterns consist of gardens and commercial use on the neighboring property. The pond itself is a hydrological modification consisting of a human made dam.

OrganizationFormalName: Sherwood Valley Band Of Pomo Indians
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: This site is located on Kawi Creek. Oak, poison oak, fir, grass, and yellow dock are the primary riparian vegetation.  The stream bed consists of small rocks, gravel, sand, and silt. The surrounding land use patterns consist of housing, a Tribal Office, and commercial use of the smoke shop and casino/caf including a parking lot with oil stained parking spaces and issues with the caf grease trap leaking used cooking oil onto the ground. The neighboring property has cattle grazing and they have been know to cross the fence on to Tribal land. The site is located near a culvert where the creek goes under Sherwood Hill Drive.
